'''Marcus Junius D. f. M. n. Silanus''' was [[Roman consul|consul]] in 25 BC with [[Augustus|Gaius Julius Caesar Octavianus]], the emperor Augustus.

==Biography==
Silanus was a descendant of the noble Roman house of the [[Junia (gens)|Junii Silani]].  He was probably the son of [[Decimus Junius Silanus (consul)|Decimus Junius Silanus]], consul in 62 BC, and [[Servilia (mother of Marcus Junius Brutus)|Servilia]], and perhaps the grandson of [[Marcus Junius Silanus (consul 109 BC)|Marcus Junius Silanus]], consul in 109 BC.  He was the brother-in-law of [[Marcus Aemilius Lepidus (triumvir)|Marcus Aemilius Lepidus]], the triumvir.<ref>''[[Oxford Classical Dictionary]]'', 2nd Ed. (1970).</ref><ref>''[[Realencyclop√§die der Classischen Altertumswissenschaft]]''.</ref>

Silanus served as one of [[Julius Caesar]]'s [[legatus|legates]] in 53 BC.<ref>Anthon & Smith, pg. 812</ref><ref>In his monumental [[Thomas Robert Shannon Broughton|''Magistrates of the Roman Republic'']], [[Thomas Robert Shannon Broughton|T.R.S. Broughton]] suggests that the consul of 25 BC might be distinguished from the legate of 53 BC. Broughton, pg. 230</ref>  He supported his brother-in-law Lepidus in 44 BC after Caesar's murder, accompanying Lepidus over the [[Alps]].  The following year, Lepidus sent him with a detachment of troops to join [[Mark Antony|Marcus Antonius]] at [[Battle of Mutina|Mutina]],<ref>Anthon & Smith, pg. 812; Syme, pg. 178</ref> but refused to accept responsibility for the help which Silanus gave.<ref>Broughton, pg. 352</ref>  After falling out of favor with the [[Second Triumvirate|triumvirs]], in 39 he fled to [[Sextus Pompey|Sextus Pompeius]].<ref>Syme, pg. 189</ref>  He was able to return to Antonius's service under the terms of the [[Pact of Misenum]].<ref>Broughton, Vol III, pg. 114</ref>  Silanus later served under Antonius in [[Achaea (Roman province)|Greece]] and [[Macedonia (Roman province)|Macedonia]]<ref>Broughton, pg. 415</ref> from 34 to 32, with the title of ''[[Quaestor]] pro consule'' or perhaps ''[[Proquaestor]]''.<ref>Broughton, pgs. 359 & 411</ref>  Around this time he was also elected as an [[Augur]].<ref>Broughton, pg. 412</ref>

Before the [[Battle of Actium]], Silanus went over to Octavianus.<ref>Syme, pg. 296</ref>  The future emperor raised him to the [[Patrician (ancient Rome)|Patriciate]] in 30 BC,<ref>Syme, pg. 382</ref> and they held the consulship together in 25.<ref>[[Thomas Robert Shannon Broughton|T. Robert S. Broughton]], ''The Magistrates of the Roman Republic'' (1952).</ref><ref>''[[Oxford Classical Dictionary]]'', 2nd Ed. (1970).</ref>

Silanus' grandson, [[Marcus Junius Silanus Torquatus (consul AD 19)|Marcus Junius Silanus Torquatus]], was consul in AD 19, and married a great-granddaughter of Augustus.<ref>''[[Oxford Classical Dictionary]]'', 2nd Ed. (1970).</ref>

