'''Lord John Frederick Gordon Hallyburton''' [[Royal Guelphic Order|GCH]] (15 August 1799 ‚Äì 29 September 1878) was a Scottish naval officer and Member of Parliament.

He was born [[the Honourable]] '''John Frederick Gordon''', third son of [[George Gordon, 9th Marquess of Huntly|George Gordon, 5th Earl of Aboyne]] by his wife Catherine Anne, daughter of [[Sir Charles Cope, 2nd Baronet]]. On 28 May 1836 his father succeeded as 9th [[Marquess of Huntly]].<ref name=bp4>[[James Balfour Paul]], ''The Scots Peerage'', 1907, [https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul vol. 4], p 559</ref><ref name=cracrofthuntly>Patrick Cracroft-Brennan, [http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/Huntly1599.htm Huntly, Marquess of (S, 1599)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011125912/http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/Huntly1599.htm |date=11 October 2010 }}, Cracroft's Peerage. Accessed 23 October 2011</ref> He reached the rank of [[Captain (Royal Navy)|Captain]] in the [[Royal Navy]] on 4 August 1836.<ref>[http://www.pbenyon1.plus.com/Nbd/exec/H/Index.html RN Executive Officers - 1790-1879 "H"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501092147/http://www.pbenyon1.plus.com/Nbd/exec/H/Index.html |date=1 May 2012 }}. Accessed 23 October 2011</ref>

On 24 August 1836 Gordon was married to [[Lady Augusta Gordon|Lady Augusta Kennedy-Erskine]] (17 June 1803 ‚Äì 8 December 1865), widow since 6 April 1831 of the Hon. John Kennedy Erskine of Dun, second son of [[Archibald Kennedy, 1st Marquess of Ailsa]].<ref name=bp2/> She was born Augusta [[FitzClarence]], the fourth daughter of [[William IV of the United Kingdom|King William IV]] by the actress [[Dorothea Jordan]],<ref name=cracroftmunster>Patrick Cracroft-Brennan, [http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index753.htm Munster, Earl of (UK, 1831 - 2000)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513022203/http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index753.htm |date=13 May 2012 }}, Cracroft's Peerage. Accessed 23 October 2011</ref> and had been [[Royal Warrant of Precedence|raised to the rank of a Marquess's daughter]] on 24 May 1831.<ref name=ScotMPs152/> By this marriage he gained three step-children:
* William Henry Kennedy Erskine (1 July 1828 ‚Äì 5 September 1870), who inherited the [[House of Dun]] in [[Forfarshire]] and served as a captain in the [[17th Lancers]]. He married Catherine Jones on 18 November 1862 and had issue, including the writer [[Violet Jacob]].<ref name=bp2>James Balfour Paul, ''The Scots Peerage'', 1904, [https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun02paul vol. 2], p. 499-500</ref>
* [[Wilhelmina FitzClarence, Countess of Munster|Wilhelmina Kennedy Erskine]] (26 June 1830 ‚Äì 9 October 1906), who married [[William George FitzClarence, 2nd Earl of Munster]] on 17 April 1855 and had issue.<ref name=bp2/><ref name=cracroftmunster/>
* Augusta Millicent Anne Mary Kennedy Erskine (11 May 1831 ‚Äì 11 February 1895), who married [[James Hay Wemyss]] on 17 April 1855  and had issue.<ref name=bp2/>
They had no children of their own.<ref name=bp4/><ref name=cracrofthuntly/><ref name=ScotMPs152/> Gordon was made a Knight Grand Cross in the civil division of the [[Royal Guelphic Order]] on 22 August 1836<ref>John Haydn and Horace Ockerby, ''The Book of Dignities'', 1894 reprinted 1969, p. 787</ref> and a [[Lord of the Bedchamber]] to the King on 26 October that year.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=19433|page=1900|date=1 November 1836}}</ref>

In the [[1841 United Kingdom general election|general election of 1841]] Gordon was elected to Parliament for [[Forfarshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Forfarshire]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=19999|page=1856|date=16 July 1841}}</ref> succeeding his uncle [[Lord Douglas Gordon-Hallyburton]].<ref name=rayment>Leigh Rayment, [http://www.leighrayment.com/commons/Fcommons.htm The House of Commons - Constituencies beginning with "F"]. Accessed 23 October 2011</ref> He also inherited his uncle's estates, and assumed the additional surname of '''Hallyburton''' in 1843.<ref name=bp4/><ref name=ScotMPs152/><ref>{{Hansard-contribs | lord-john-gordon | Lord John Gordon }}</ref> He was made a [[Deputy Lieutenant]] for Forfarshire on 5 June 1847<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=20744|page=2179|date=15 June 1847}}</ref> and re-elected for the county in the [[1847 United Kingdom general election|general election of that year]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=20764|page=2951|date=13 August 1847}}</ref> He remained in Parliament until [[1852 United Kingdom general election|the 1852 election]],<ref name=ScotMPs152>Joseph Foster, ''[https://archive.org/details/cu31924030499002 Members of Parliament, Scotland]'', 1882, p. 152</ref> when he was replaced by [[Lauderdale Maule]].<ref name=rayment/>

Gordon-Hallyburton was promoted to [[Rear-Admiral (Royal Navy)|Rear-Admiral]] on the Reserve Half Pay List on 12 May 1857,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=22003|page=1770|date=19 May 1857}}</ref> and promoted in the same list to [[Vice-Admiral (Royal Navy)|Vice-Admiral]] on 4 November 1863<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=22787|page=5304|date=10 November 1863}}</ref> and full [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|Admiral]] on 8 April 1868.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=23370|page=2221|date=14 April 1868}}</ref>

He lived at Hallyburton House near [[Coupar Angus]].<ref>Perth Post Office Directory 1865: List of Noblemen and Gentlemens Country Seats</ref>

