'''Ibrahim Fehmi Pa≈üa''' (born 1838, in [[Albania]], died 1896). He graduated from [[Kuleli Military High School]] in 1863, then from the Military Academy (Mektebi Harbiyeyi ≈ûahane) in 1867 in [[Constantinople]]. Prince Ibrahim was appointed with full powers in military and civilian affairs in [[Baghdad]] in 1891. A provisional law granted him emergency powers in May of that year. All cabinet decrees from Constantinople related to Baghdad became subject to his approval.

==Education==
Upon receiving a Western education in [[France]], where he attended the √©cole  d'√©tat  major, he returned home,  on the death of his elder brother and became heir to his uncle, [[Isma'il Pasha|Ismail Pasha]], Wali of [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]]. Ismail employed him in the next few years on missions abroad, to the [[Pope]], the [[Emperor Napoleon III]] and the Sultan of [[Ottoman Empire]]. In 1869 he was dispatched at the head of an army of 18,000 to quell an insurrection in Sudan, and this he successfully accomplished.



